## Avoid Layer-Based Organization

Avoid structures such as:

```text
src/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ controllers/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ services/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ models/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ repositories/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ views/
в””в”Ђв”Ђ utils/
```

These structures scale poorly because unrelated features become tightly coupled.

## File Placement Rules

New code must be placed inside the feature that owns the behavior.

Examples:

* Authentication logic в†’ `features/authentication/`
* Billing logic в†’ `features/billing/`
* Search logic в†’ `features/search/`

Do not create global folders for feature-specific code.

## Shared Code

Code belongs in `shared/` only if:

1. It is used by multiple features.
2. It has no business-specific behavior.
3. It can be reused without knowledge of a particular feature.

Examples:

```text
shared/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ networking/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ database/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ logging/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ configuration/
в””в”Ђв”Ђ utilities/
```

## Tests

Tests should live close to the feature they validate.

```text
features/
в””в”Ђв”Ђ search/
    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ implementation/
    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ tests/
    в””в”Ђв”Ђ docs/
```

or

```text
features/
в””в”Ђв”Ђ search/
    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ search.py
    в””в”Ђв”Ђ test_search.py
```

depending on language conventions.

## Documentation

Feature-specific documentation should live inside the feature folder.

```text
features/
в””в”Ђв”Ђ billing/
    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ SPECS.md
    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ README.md
    в””в”Ђв”Ђ implementation/
```

## Refactoring Guidance

When modifying code:

* Prefer moving code toward the owning feature.
* Avoid introducing new global layer folders.
* Keep dependencies localized.
* Minimize cross-feature coupling.
* Preserve clear feature boundaries.

## Language Independence

This rule applies equally to:

* Swift
* Python
* Rust
* TypeScript
* JavaScript
* Kotlin
* Java
* Go
* C#
* PHP

The organization principle remains the same regardless of language or framework.
